## Why Cursor Pagination is Superior Here

| Concern | Offset | Cursor |
|---|---|---|
| **Performance at depth** | `OFFSET 10000` forces the DB to scan and discard 10,000 rows before returning results — O(offset) cost | WHERE clause with an index on `(created_at DESC, id DESC)` seeks directly to the right row — O(1) cost |
| **Consistency under writes** | A new post inserted while a user pages causes every subsequent offset to shift, producing duplicate or skipped rows | The cursor anchors to a specific row by value; inserts/deletes behind the cursor are invisible to the in-flight traversal |
| **COUNT(*) removed** | Required a full table scan on every request to compute `totalPages` | Not needed — `hasMore` is derived for free from the N+1 fetch |
| **Index utilization** | DB must count rows from the start regardless of index | The compound index on `(created_at, id)` is used for both the `WHERE` seek and the `ORDER BY` — a single index range scan |

The one trade-off is that cursor pagination is **non-random-access** — you can't jump to page 7 directly. For an infinite-scroll or "load more" feed (the dominant pattern for a post timeline), that's perfectly acceptable and the performance wins at scale are significant.

